WEBVTT

00:00:02.500 --> 00:00:07.000
Quarantine economy

00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:16.400
Good afternoon, welcome to the next panel
discussion of Going Digital 2020 conference.

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:23.830
This panel is devoted to a topic
that is more and more interesting,

00:00:24.030 --> 00:00:30.000
given that we saw various
restrictive measures in last months.

00:00:30.200 --> 00:00:32.700
The first came in the spring,
the spring quarantine,

00:00:32.900 --> 00:00:35.000
and then we had a loosening of the summer,

00:00:35.568 --> 00:00:38.680
and winter quarantine came
and we are now somehow dealing with it.

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:41.800
We see that the economy will open again,

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:47.250
so this panel is devoted to the so-called
quarantine economy or economy during quarantine.

00:00:47.450 --> 00:00:52.480
My name is Aneta Zachová,
I am the editor-in-chief of the euractiv.cz.

00:00:52.680 --> 00:00:58.150
I'm glad to be able to moderate
this panel discussion.

00:00:59.500 --> 00:01:01.350
I have great guests here,

00:01:01.550 --> 00:01:06.330
Mikuláš Peksa sitting next to me,
MEP for the Czech Pirate Party.

00:01:07.114 --> 00:01:08.565
Good day.
Good day.

00:01:08.765 --> 00:01:14.885
Online joined us Mrs. Danuše Nerudová,
Rector of Mendel University in Brno.

00:01:16.085 --> 00:01:19.700
Mrs. Helena Horská,
Raiffeisenbank's chief economist,

00:01:20.900 --> 00:01:24.580
Mrs. Šárka Homfray, a lawyer and trade unionist,
also accepted the invitation.

00:01:24.780 --> 00:01:29.650
And Mr. Karel Gargulák, an analyst from EDUin.

00:01:29.850 --> 00:01:35.800
We have an hour-long discussion ahead of us,
so I will probably end introduction,

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.000
because I am very curious about
what I will hear from our dear guests.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:47.000
Let's look at the first topic,
for many people the quarantine economy

00:01:47.200 --> 00:01:51.320
means the transition from working in offices
to home offices.

00:01:52.500 --> 00:02:00.300
I wonder how this move to home-offices
or teleworking, as it is also called,

00:02:00.500 --> 00:02:04.280
how did it affect the economy?

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:07.500
I would like us to talk not only purely
about the Czech one,

00:02:07.700 --> 00:02:11.020
but also to look at the whole European economy.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:15.230
I'll take advantage of the fact that
I have two great economists here,

00:02:15.864 --> 00:02:21.200
so first I'd ask the Mrs Rector,
if she could answer the same question.

00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:27.700
How did the transition from offices
to the home office actually affect the economy?

00:02:27.900 --> 00:02:29.100
Please Mrs Rector

00:02:30.800 --> 00:02:34.880
Good afternoon,
I would like to thank you for the invitation,

00:02:35.080 --> 00:02:37.000
it is a great honor for you to invite me.

00:02:38.200 --> 00:02:41.150
As for how homeoffice has affected the economy,

00:02:41.350 --> 00:02:43.300
it has manifested itself in several ways.

00:02:43.500 --> 00:02:46.770
It manifested itself primarily
in what we all clearly observe,

00:02:46.970 --> 00:02:50.600
and that is that when
you look up at the sky, you don't see any lines.

00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:53.180
So this is one of the consequences of home offices,

00:02:53.380 --> 00:02:57.830
because I think that business trips
have dropped by almost 80 percent.

00:02:57.831 --> 00:03:04.241
I think the MEP could explain
how full the planes used to be

00:03:04.441 --> 00:03:07.100
because everyone flew to a working
meeting in Brussels.

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:11.670
And now he's either driving
or sitting in a half-empty plane.

00:03:11.870 --> 00:03:17.240
So basically it has a big impact on traffic,
that's one thing.

00:03:17.440 --> 00:03:24.880
It certainly has an impact on the online economy,

00:03:25.080 --> 00:03:30.000
because when people moved to a home office
and spent most of it at home.

00:03:30.200 --> 00:03:35.270
Of course, thanks to closed shops,
the online economy sector is developing.

00:03:35.470 --> 00:03:37.600
And, unfortunately, it has consequences,

00:03:37.800 --> 00:03:40.575
we can discuss that, unfortunately,
as how it was set up

00:03:40.575 --> 00:03:46.750
with the unfortunate settings and selection,
it happened that some shops

00:03:46.950 --> 00:03:50.660
were discriminated against
and did not have a fair conditions.

00:03:50.860 --> 00:03:55.400
It will definitely have an impact
on the real estate market.

00:03:55.600 --> 00:03:59.980
The companies will significantly reconsider

00:04:00.180 --> 00:04:04.000
how they will use their office space
for the coming years.

00:04:04.200 --> 00:04:12.210
Some want to reduce it, some will change
amount of employees with own office,

00:04:14.500 --> 00:04:18.165
or on the contrary some want to have
a higher standard, want more space

00:04:18.365 --> 00:04:20.800
so that employees are separated from each other.

00:04:21.700 --> 00:04:27.800
Last but not least, I think covid means
that some myths have fallen

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:33.100
and that the resistance of employers
to send people at home office has fallen,

00:04:33.300 --> 00:04:37.700
because one big myth was
that people at the home office are inefficient,

00:04:37.900 --> 00:04:43.950
because they don't work, but I think this crisis has shown that in many cases

00:04:44.150 --> 00:04:47.850
it is not true at all
and the efficiency is far greater,

00:04:48.050 --> 00:04:51.950
If all really went into those digital platforms.

00:04:52.150 --> 00:04:57.000
For me, it is one big change in transport,
in the real estate market

00:04:57.200 --> 00:05:02.000
and, of course, it will also be indirectly
a change in the construction industry,

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:08.450
because office space will be built
according to new standards and new patterns.

00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:15.250
Thank you very much for this introductory part
about how the transition to the digital environment

00:05:15.450 --> 00:05:22.500
has affected our classic economy,
such as the real estate market.

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:29.700
I would now have a question for Mrs Horská
and I would remain at this economic level.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:41.250
Mrs. Horská, can you tell us what positive effects
this transition had to the digital environment,

00:05:41.450 --> 00:05:49.450
to the Czech and European economy,
and whether we can learn from it for the future?

00:05:49.650 --> 00:05:53.490
How to work in the coming years?
Please, Mrs. Horská.

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:57.100
I also thank you very much for the invitation,

00:05:57.102 --> 00:06:01.600
I hope that we will have a very interesting
and fruitful discussion.

00:06:01.800 --> 00:06:07.850
As for the question, the positive impact
of homeoffice was certainly visible,

00:06:07.863 --> 00:06:14.600
because without homeoffice, we would be less
able to get covid-19 under control.

00:06:14.800 --> 00:06:20.930
However, it is necessary to realize that
homeoffice is not a model of work for everyone.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:23.700
I think it's good to realize.

00:06:23.900 --> 00:06:29.900
It is, as it is often said,
a possibility for white-collar workers,

00:06:30.100 --> 00:06:35.600
while blue-collar workers, that means,
people working in normal industrial production,

00:06:35.800 --> 00:06:42.900
unfortunately cannot benefit from homeofice yet, e
ven at this time

00:06:43.100 --> 00:06:49.500
when we should move towards automation,
robotization and then digitization.

00:06:50.350 --> 00:06:55.450
It is necessary to realize that
in Czechia, according to the CERGE study,

00:06:55.650 --> 00:06:58.500
the home office regarded just a third of Czechs,

00:06:58.700 --> 00:07:02.360
which means that it is not even half of the people,

00:07:02.560 --> 00:07:08.300
and the home office was focused mainly
on large cities.

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:11.500
Especially Prague and large regional cities.

00:07:11.700 --> 00:07:15.000
So the home office in general, not only
in the Czech Republic but also in Europe,

00:07:15.200 --> 00:07:20.000
is also dependent on a certain degree of urbanization.

00:07:20.200 --> 00:07:25.430
It can be used in cities, but it is less
well used in industrial fields.

00:07:25.630 --> 00:07:31.200
Also there is difference in application of home offices
between economies that are more industrial,

00:07:31.400 --> 00:07:36.500
such as the Czech Republic but also Germany,
in contrast to other countries,

00:07:36.700 --> 00:07:44.000
such as the United Kingdom, the Netherlands,
which are countries more focused on services.

00:07:44.200 --> 00:07:49.800
At the services, of course, we can imagine
that the home office is much more used.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.450
And another aspect is very interesting,

00:07:52.650 --> 00:07:58.150
homeoffice is rather offered
to people who have higher education,

00:07:58.350 --> 00:08:03.500
because they work in those fields
that are managerial,

00:08:03.700 --> 00:08:07.350
which are quite similar to services,

00:08:07.550 --> 00:08:13.390
or when they already work in an industrial enterprise
so they work in those managerial positions ,

00:08:13.590 --> 00:08:20.250
which may just be relocated somewhere
other than industrial production.

00:08:20.450 --> 00:08:26.100
So when we talk about home office, I would like to
emphasize that we're talking about Czechia,

00:08:26.300 --> 00:08:28.500
only about a third of the population

00:08:28.700 --> 00:08:34.500
and it is necessary to consider
that two-thirds did not have this chance.

00:08:34.700 --> 00:08:41.300
That means saleswomen, drivers,
people standing at the production lines

00:08:41.500 --> 00:08:47.850
did not have this option and had to find
other ways to deal with the covid situation.

00:08:48.250 --> 00:08:55.000
And I think that the good thing, as Danuše
has already mentioned, is the factor

00:08:55.200 --> 00:09:00.700
that people have lost such shyness,
fears of home office and perhaps

00:09:00.900 --> 00:09:05.800
even bigger worries about the home office
had employers, company managers.

00:09:06.300 --> 00:09:13.565
I have to confirm what the Danuse said,
in our bank the issue of home office

00:09:13.765 --> 00:09:18.410
was very much disscussed and I have to say
that both approaches appeared there,

00:09:18.610 --> 00:09:24.200
as the positive progressive approach that said
yes let's use home office,

00:09:24.400 --> 00:09:29.570
because by the way from the survey
we did among our employees, we know

00:09:29.770 --> 00:09:35.800
that employee satisfaction increased
due to the fact that they were given a chance

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:41.180
to use the home office.
Again, not everyone in the bank got this chance.

00:09:41.380 --> 00:09:46.580
Unfortunately, we also have professions
that could not use the home office,

00:09:46.780 --> 00:09:48.350
for example people at the counters,
at the cash desks.

00:09:48.550 --> 00:09:53.450
But employee satisfaction has increased,
which is certainly good,

00:09:53.650 --> 00:10:01.000
but we also had managers who
opposed the change a bit, who were afraid

00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:05.000
that in a way they would lose control of their employees.

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:12.150
We also need to think about managerial skills,
how to educate managers

00:10:12.350 --> 00:10:16.630
and how to teach people to manage remotely,

00:10:16.830 --> 00:10:19.400
how to work with a team remotely,

00:10:19.600 --> 00:10:24.700
and I think that at this we have moved
really forward in a few months.

00:10:24.900 --> 00:10:29.650
and things we would have been doing for years,

00:10:29.850 --> 00:10:35.340
we managed in a few months due to the pressure.

00:10:36.100 --> 00:10:39.239
We had to implement the change

00:10:39.439 --> 00:10:42.200
Even I had to learn to manage my team remotely

00:10:42.400 --> 00:10:49.000
and I actually take advantage of these benefits,
from the new knowledge I learned.

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:52.750
Acceleration of big changes that would otherwise take a long time,

00:10:52.950 --> 00:10:58.600
it means that from  business as usual,
we got into that acceleration

00:10:58.800 --> 00:11:00.480
to the speed of changes.

00:11:00.680 --> 00:11:05.680
And I have to say that at work it was also
reflected in a change in the work environment,

00:11:05.880 --> 00:11:12.950
as Danuše said, that the design of the offices,
common areas, will actually change.

00:11:13.150 --> 00:11:17.100
It's not necessarily about needing more space,

00:11:17.300 --> 00:11:22.570
but we will use the existing space for
fewer people,

00:11:22.770 --> 00:11:30.160
because we assume that maybe every
third person will take turns with a colleague

00:11:30.360 --> 00:11:31.920
and the third will be at homeoffice.

00:11:32.120 --> 00:11:37.000
So there is really a change in the work
environment, in the organization of work

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:40.500
that we might experienced in the next five years,

00:11:40.700 --> 00:11:42.320
and now we will experience it in a single year.

00:11:42.520 --> 00:11:45.100
So the keyword is acceleration.

00:11:45.999 --> 00:11:54.400
Thank you very much, Mrs. Horská, for this
really nice overview of the economic change.

00:11:54.600 --> 00:11:59.800
You were talking about the employees about
the large variety of people,

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:06.660
who couldn't transition to the home office,
and stayed at cash registers or at production lines.

00:12:06.860 --> 00:12:09.750
I will leverage of the fact
that Šárka Homfray is here with us

00:12:09.950 --> 00:12:17.850
and I would like to ask her if she thinks
that governments, not only the Czech one

00:12:17.845 --> 00:12:26.000
took care about these employees
during quarantine economy?

00:12:25.920 --> 00:12:27.380
Please, Mrs. Homfray.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:36.400
Hello, I hope you can hear me well
and thank you for the invitation as well.

00:12:36.600 --> 00:12:45.000
Frankly, I don't think we were able to
take such good care of them as a state.

00:12:45.200 --> 00:12:49.150
We all know that, there was not enough
protective equipment in the spring.

00:12:49.350 --> 00:12:52.210
This was, of course, a worldwide problem.

00:12:52.410 --> 00:13:00.500
Unfortunately, I must say that many employers
did not buy enough protective equipment

00:13:00.700 --> 00:13:05.600
for their employees even in the fall
when it was more available.

00:13:05.800 --> 00:13:08.900
Because truth is that

00:13:09.100 --> 00:13:15.600
many employers have no legal obligation to
equip their employees with this equipment.

00:13:16.800 --> 00:13:23.500
Furthermore, we felt quite a great
reluctance of a number of employers,

00:13:23.700 --> 00:13:27.800
especially in the autumn,
to allow home office or work from home,

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.100
even there where it was possible in the spring.

00:13:30.300 --> 00:13:38.350
There was a significantly lower will to
further measures such as dividing employees

00:13:38.550 --> 00:13:47.500
into non-meeting groups, workplace
modifications, reduction of working hours

00:13:47.700 --> 00:13:52.150
or a reduction in production, unless
the government measures forced them to do so.

00:13:52.123 --> 00:14:00.000
There are, of course, employers who did this,
for example, banks cut working hours

00:14:00.200 --> 00:14:05.500
at their branches even though
it was not restricted, it was their will,

00:14:06.300 --> 00:14:09.540
but then there were a number
of employers who did not do anything.

00:14:09.740 --> 00:14:14.500
It was really clear that during the second wave
the will was even lower for any restrictions

00:14:14.700 --> 00:14:15.900
than it was  in during spring.

00:14:16.100 --> 00:14:22.000
It must be said that this is not
remembered on this situations by our legislation,

00:14:22.200 --> 00:14:24.500
by the Labor Law or in other regulations,

00:14:24.700 --> 00:14:30.200
especially by those related to hygiene
related to safety during work.

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:38.500
The crisis law, especially the enforcement of
violations of these crisis measures,

00:14:38.700 --> 00:14:43.750
is not completely set for the situation
that happened.

00:14:43.950 --> 00:14:47.180
Inspection bodies do not have the capacity to monitor such things.

00:14:47.380 --> 00:14:52.500
It was not clear for many of those measures if
violations would be enforceable at all.

00:14:52.700 --> 00:14:59.700
So I have to say that maybe will or
at least there was an effort to

00:14:59.900 --> 00:15:08.700
instruct the employers to provide
the employees, but the small enforceability

00:15:08.900 --> 00:15:16.800
of the measures simply
caused that no one did it voluntarily.

00:15:18.400 --> 00:15:22.500
Thank you very much.
I would go a little further.

00:15:22.700 --> 00:15:30.500
In the quarantined economy, we are witnessing that some sectors

00:15:30.700 --> 00:15:45.000
are facing huge losses, almost bankrupcy,
but there are sectors, who are winning now.

00:15:46.200 --> 00:15:53.330
Mr. Peksa, can you give us any
insight into which sectors within Europe,

00:15:53.530 --> 00:15:58.600
in the context of what is happening,
are strengthening and if is it good or bad?

00:15:58.800 --> 00:16:05.780
We know it is mainly digital sector,
new platforms and applications are being made,

00:16:05.980 --> 00:16:13.210
We have witnessed a digital boom,
do you think that this is a good thing?

00:16:13.410 --> 00:16:15.960
Do you think it will last to future?

00:16:16.160 --> 00:16:22.300
I would not say it good, because the process
or the transition that is going on now

00:16:22.500 --> 00:16:27.580
is actually very stormy, very fast and
the change is very revolutionary

00:16:27.780 --> 00:16:30.200
and many people suffer a lot because of it.

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:35.510
On the other hand, as has been said here,
it is  a great acceleration of this process,

00:16:35.710 --> 00:16:40.200
because we have had various programs,
such as Digital Europe and so for many years before

00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:44.000
which were supposed to digitize Europe.

00:16:44.200 --> 00:16:48.150
Now we have basically got into the situation
that during the month we are in a position

00:16:48.350 --> 00:16:50.200
that we must be digital, no matter what.

00:16:50.400 --> 00:16:55.000
So we started to digitize hurriedly,
because we had simply no other option left.

00:16:55.200 --> 00:16:58.400
I think it is true that some were
prepared for it,

00:16:58.600 --> 00:17:02.000
at the same time it is true that some
were tragically unprepared for it

00:17:02.200 --> 00:17:07.000
nd they then had a big problem adapting to it.

00:17:07.200 --> 00:17:11.100
These processes change a lot,
it was seen during the first quarantine,

00:17:11.300 --> 00:17:17.750
when restaurants came under pressure
that they could not open,

00:17:17.950 --> 00:17:24.320
and they started to react relatively quickly
by cooking food and letting it be delivered.

00:17:24.520 --> 00:17:30.700
So I think one of those sectors that has
experienced a huge boom is delivery services.

00:17:30.900 --> 00:17:35.000
Although we will have to think about
how it works,

00:17:35.200 --> 00:17:43.800
because what I found out, the conditions
that employees have there, are often quite critical,

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:47.000
but it is actually one of those industries
that was developing

00:17:47.200 --> 00:17:49.580
and it was not so obvious before.

00:17:49.780 --> 00:17:55.000
I think a lot depends on the company
or on the institution.

00:17:55.200 --> 00:17:59.050
I remember, and it was mentioned here,
within the European Parliament

00:17:59.250 --> 00:18:03.500
it was somehow the custom that everyone
just flew to Brussels,

00:18:03.700 --> 00:18:06.999
they all met there physically and
it was impossible to do otherwise.

00:18:07.199 --> 00:18:10.720
Then suddenly in the situation
when a package of legislation appeared

00:18:10.920 --> 00:18:17.150
that had to be approved, or voted about it
and it could not be done in person,

00:18:17.350 --> 00:18:20.800
we began to invent alternative solutions
how to vote online.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.500
How to deal with these things.

00:18:23.700 --> 00:18:29.530
It was really very spontaneous, I would
often say that in terms of cyber security,

00:18:29.730 --> 00:18:34.200
it could be done better,
but in the end it happened.

00:18:34.400 --> 00:18:40.300
Well, I think those who were right, said before
the crisis that it was necessary to digitize,

00:18:40.500 --> 00:18:43.700
modernize because they
were better prepared for it.

00:18:43.900 --> 00:18:50.000
For example journalists have asked me many times,
how the Pirate Party has dealt with this.

00:18:50.200 --> 00:18:53.250
We didn't notice it,
because we've worked online before,

00:18:53.450 --> 00:18:56.000
which means it wasn't really a change for us.

00:18:56.200 --> 00:18:59.999
We just kept using the same tools.

00:19:00.880 --> 00:19:03.700
I found out that somewhere else
they have magical problems

00:19:03.900 --> 00:19:08.500
such as the resignation of the party chairman
nd they cannot convene an online congress

00:19:08.700 --> 00:19:11.000
and they don´t know how replace him.
So they are in dead end,

00:19:11.200 --> 00:19:16.600
and they're still using the resigned person,
because they just can't get a new one.

00:19:16.800 --> 00:19:19.700
So it probably depends on what, how and where.

00:19:19.900 --> 00:19:25.700
I think we have realized that we have great
shortcomings throughout the organization,

00:19:25.900 --> 00:19:33.650
because until February 2020, healthcare
or preparation for these pandemic crises

00:19:33.850 --> 00:19:37.000
was wholly considered the domain of the
Member States of the European Union,

00:19:37.200 --> 00:19:41.800
So it means, when in March came the question
"so where does EU have maks,

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:48.120
because we don't have any and where are
the warehouses from which you will supply us?"

00:19:48.320 --> 00:19:52.800
So there were none. So logically
arosed the question where to take.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:58.000
I am glad that we managed to
convince the European Commission,

00:19:58.200 --> 00:20:02.850
that it had started solving the problem,
so that sometime during the summer,

00:20:03.050 --> 00:20:08.970
deliveries from central purchasings organized
by the European Commission began to flow,

00:20:09.170 --> 00:20:13.700
although I think that even at this moment,
any European treatiet order this.

00:20:13.900 --> 00:20:19.420
It just does it because such a situation
has occurred and it just had to be.

00:20:19.620 --> 00:20:25.240
So I think we've just adapted in a number of areas,
and that adaptation will take place.

00:20:25.440 --> 00:20:29.800
It might be better to think about it in advance,
but after the battle, everybody is general.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:34.600
Thank you very much, we talked
about acceleration, about adaptation

00:20:34.800 --> 00:20:40.100
and I think, that in this it will be
an important role to actually prepare it,

00:20:40.300 --> 00:20:48.100
or, they should be prepared already, but
somehow to lead people to be able to adapt.

00:20:48.300 --> 00:20:51.200
Education plays a key role in this,

00:20:51.400 --> 00:20:57.940
I would as Karel Gargulák
from EDUin, who deals with education,

00:20:58.140 --> 00:21:04.310
and I would like to know if the current
school system, or the education system,

00:21:04.510 --> 00:21:10.760
is actually ready for these changes that have
occurred in the European and global economy,

00:21:10.960 --> 00:21:19.250
if now Czech schools will be able to
produce graduates who will be prepared

00:21:19.450 --> 00:21:24.000
or this relatively different reality
than was needed 5, 10 years ago.

00:21:24.200 --> 00:21:25.660
Please, Mr. Gargulák.

00:21:25.860 --> 00:21:33.200
Hello, thank you very much for the word,
I tried to indicate it in my first post,

00:21:33.400 --> 00:21:41.500
covid and the closure of the economy
slapped the system in the sense

00:21:41.700 --> 00:21:46.010
that when we were talking about the potential of
